05279nam a22008775i 9780231552042DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019049701  a97802315520427 a10.7312/coll197202doi  a(DE-B1597)566389  a(OCoLC)1129395205  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aB162b.C65 2020 4aB162b.C65 2020 7aREL0070402bisacsh04a294.3/912231 aCollins, Steven, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWisdom as a Way of Life :bTheravāda Buddhism Reimagined /cSteven Collins; ed. by Justin McDaniel. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tEDITOR’S INTRODUCTION -- tPart One. WISDOM -- tPart Two. PRACTICES OF SELF -- tCONCLUSION -- tAFTERWORD -- tNOTES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis wide-ranging and powerful book argues that Theravāda Buddhism provides ways of thinking about the self that can reinvigorate the humanities and offer broader insights into how to learn and how to act. Steven Collins argues that Buddhist philosophy should be approached in the spirit of its historical teachers and visionaries, who saw themselves not as preservers of an archaic body of rules but as part of a timeless effort to understand what it means to lead a worthy life. He contends that Buddhism should be studied philosophically, literarily, and ethically using its own vocabulary and rhetorical tools. Approached in this manner, Buddhist notions of the self help us rethink contemporary ideas of self-care and the promotion of human flourishing.Collins details the insights of Buddhist texts and practices that promote the ideal of active and engaged learning, offering an expansive and lyrical reflection on Theravāda approaches to meditation, asceticism, and physical training. He explores views of monastic life and contemplative practices as complementing and reinforcing textual learning, and argues that the Buddhist tenet that the study of philosophy and ethics involves both rigorous reading and an ascetic lifestyle has striking resonance with modern and postmodern ideas. A bold reappraisal of the history of Buddhist literature and practice, Wisdom as a Way of Life offers students and scholars across the disciplines a nuanced understanding of the significance of Buddhist ways of knowing for the world today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aAnātman. 0aAnātman. 0aBuddhist philosophy. 0aSelf (Philosophy) 0aSelf (Philosophy). 0aTheravāda Buddhism. 0aTheravāda Buddhism. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / Theravada.2bisacsh1 aArnold, Dan.1 aHallisey, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHallisey, Charles.1 aMcDaniel, Justin Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDaniel, Justin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311071097708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020 Englishz978311070477808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020z9783110704570oZDB-23-DGF40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/coll1972040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231552042423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231552042.jpg  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPL